In .NET MAUI, use `Application.Current.RequestedTheme` and the `RequestedThemeChanged` event. To force a theme, set `Application.Current.UserAppTheme`.

```csharp
// Detect current system theme
AppTheme currentTheme = Application.Current.RequestedTheme;
// Returns AppTheme.Light, AppTheme.Dark, or AppTheme.Unspecified

// Subscribe to real-time theme changes
Application.Current.RequestedThemeChanged += (s, e) =>
{
    AppTheme newTheme = e.RequestedTheme;
    Debug.WriteLine($"Theme changed to: {newTheme}");
    // Update UI or trigger re-theming logic here
};

// Force a specific theme (overrides system setting)
Application.Current.UserAppTheme = AppTheme.Dark;

// Revert to following the system setting
Application.Current.UserAppTheme = AppTheme.Unspecified;
```

**Key points:**

| API | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `RequestedTheme` | Read the current system theme |
| `RequestedThemeChanged` | Event fired when the OS theme toggles |
| `UserAppTheme` | Set to `AppTheme.Dark`/`Light` to force; `Unspecified` to follow system |

**In XAML**, use `AppThemeBinding` to automatically swap resources:

```xml
<Label Text="Hello"
       TextColor="{AppThemeBinding Light=Black, Dark=White}" />
```

**Typical pattern** — a settings page with a picker:

```csharp
public partial class SettingsPage : ContentPage
{
    public SettingsPage()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        themePicker.SelectedIndex = Application.Current.UserAppTheme switch
        {
            AppTheme.Light => 1,
            AppTheme.Dark  => 2,
            _              => 0  // "System default"
        };
    }

    void OnThemeSelected(object sender, EventArgs e)
    {
        Application.Current.UserAppTheme = themePicker.SelectedIndex switch
        {
            1 => AppTheme.Light,
            2 => AppTheme.Dark,
            _ => AppTheme.Unspecified
        };
        Preferences.Set("AppTheme", themePicker.SelectedIndex);
    }
}
```

Persist the user's choice with `Preferences` and re-apply it in `App()` so it survives restarts.
